As I entered the compound, I picked the smell from the gate. The rabbit house was well-built with timber, wire mesh and iron sheets. There were about 50 rabbits of different ages.
They were of mixed breed but predominantly New Zealand White. They were fed high-quality commercial feed.
Though the animals were supposed to be mainly white-coated, many of them had discoloured coats. I attributed this to dirtying from the bedding.
I noted the rabbits slept and urinated in the same place. The litter was not frequently changed and some was rotting. The state of the rabbit house explained most of the problems on the farm.
You see, in any animal setup, including humans, good hygiene is extremely important in maintaining health. It keeps stress, injuries and diseases at bay.
I was informed most of the rabbits the farm had lost were found dead without having shown signs of disease.
Others would sneeze, have heavy nasal mucous discharge and then die. I noticed some of the rabbits had red weeping eyes.
Others had inflamed hind legs and matting of the fur on the legs. In general, the rabbits looked stressed and in poor body condition.
Poor level of cleanliness and hygiene
I explained to Mary, the owner, that her main problem was the poor level of cleanliness and hygiene. The house design was fairly good but the management needed to be greatly improved.



