The rabbit odour emanated from the accumulation of rotting rabbit excreta and urine. It was further complicated by bacteria that broke down the urine to ammonia.
The ammonia caused irritation to the rabbits’ eyes and respiratory tract. This caused tearing, sneezing, coughing and infection.
The sudden deaths were most likely caused by sudden-onset pneumonia arising from stress and chemical injury by inhaled ammonia.
I diagnosed urine burns in the rabbits with inflamed hind legs. This occurs due to constant exposure to fresh and decomposing urine and ammonia. If left unattended, urine burn provides an opportunity for bacterial infection.
With the state of affairs in Mary’s rabbit house, she would never have healthy thriving animals. I treated the rabbits that had an infection with antibiotics and anti-inflammatory injections.
Dirty housing 
I advised Mary to remove all the litter in the rabbit hutches, clean them thoroughly with water and soap and then disinfect the floors.
She would also improve the house by installing a urine drainage system for each hutch.
Before leaving, I summarised to Mary the basis of ensuring good health for her rabbits. She should ensure good nutrition by continuing with high-quality commercial feed.



